  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Laws:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering crimes)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. Regulatory Agencies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice (DOJ)\n\n4. State Laws:\nMany states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.\n\n5. International Cooperation:\nThe U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force) to combat global money laundering.\n\nThese statutes typically:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish reporting requirements\n- Mandate suspicious activity reporting\n- Impose criminal and civil penalties\n- Require financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering programs\n\nThe laws are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
